<h1 id="jeju-pork">Young-Lim-Heuk-Doeji-Garden - Jeju Pork Restaurant</h1>
<p>The Jeju Black Pig is one of the biggest reasons why Koreans travel to Jeju. Most pork in Seoul comes from pink pigs, but in Jeju, most pork comes from their indigenous black pig. Native to the island, these pigs provide a tougher, crispier Korean bbq experience. It's a thicker cut of meat, without any marinade, and is cooked over familiar charcoals on your table. The meat and banchan (side veggies/kimchi) were absolutely delicious. We tried both the Jeju black pig and traditional (marinated) pork galbee. Both were fantastic. I always wrap meat in sesame leaf or lettuce, with grilled garlic and den-jang sauce. We usually grill the kimchi, too. This place had their own special dipping sauce that was heated inside a tin-foil cup, which is also absolutely delicious. We really enjoyed our dinner, even though I have a hard time eating while sitting on the floor. If you want to experience an authentic Jeju dinner, find places like Young-Lim-Heuk-Doeji-Garden.</p>
<p>When searching for good restaurants on the island, my wife has some strict criteria, and avoids popular (amongst tourists) establishments. Instead, she scours through the Naver blogs and finds restaurants where local Jeju islanders eat. We knew we were the only tourists there, as we could hear Jeju residents speaking their distinct dialect of Korean (aside from our beach attire).</p>

